,Not Recommended,451990,29051606,Posted: 5 January,all,BurnoutGT45,"TLDR: Cranks and Goggles is a very interesting concept and an impressive first effort, but there are simply other racing games that do (what this one aims for) that much better for me to recommend it to anyone but the most hardcore of racing game fans.Cranks and Goggles is asimulationarcaderacing game set in the 1920's featuring old-fashioned machines racing around locations loosely inspired by real ones around the world. Notice how I striked out simulation AND arcade, because this game tries to mix the two together.The simulation element stems from the developer's intention to base the car handling off of real car data. Now, I have no frame of reference to compare for this, but IMO the handling model here is pretty good. It's brutal and each car is VERY different, but the car handling is mostly solid. The arcade element comes from the top-down camera perspective similar to Micro Machines and racing games of that nature.All this does sound promising on paper. The problem here is in spite of a developer message on the menu stating the game is in BETA, this game literallyfeels unfinished, as if they took off the early access label (since that's where this game previously was prior to its 1.0 launch) too early. I can't speak for everyone, but when I see a game's release notes state the game has reached 1.0 Beta one day prior to its full release, to me that means the game is done content and gameplay-wise and they're just looking for bugs. Nope,what's here 3 months after said 1.0 launch is still beta, and it shows.Here's what I mean when I say this game feels unfinished:By ""lovely nostalgic soundtrack"", the devs mean: 4 racing songs that total less than 10 minutes in music time, and 1 menu song. They're not bad songs, but there's nowhere near enough of them. It gets repetitive quickly.This game's career mode is short. And by short, I mean there are 21 events, 16 of them are single races that end in approx. 3 minutes each, 4 of them are championships with 3 reused tracks each, and then one last championship with 5 more reused tracks. I know the game's price is only $5.99, but it does feel a little on the light side. There are some time trials as well, but once you get a grasp on the game's handling model, the game is over in under 4 hours (unless you want all the achievements) and getting all Golds in the time trials with a C-class vehicle is very easy. The time trial part of the game is over before it even starts. (That developer message did say something about improving time trials, but I'm just reviewing what I played.)Selecting quick race on the main menu doesn't let you pick a car and track. The game randomly picks a car and track for you. To me, it's a little odd there isn't a single race mode instead.The collision physics are just bizarre. If the car hits a wall, you'll probably spin (which makes sense considering the kinds of cars that you drive here), but if you turn into a corner with the throttle all the way down and the tire directly connects with the barrier on an angle, you'll just slide off the barrier and keep your forward momentum.There are quite a few visual hiccups. First, in-game Vsync is nonexistent, meaning the game runs way above 60fps at all times. This doesn't sound so bad, except in-game the motion looks really choppy due to the fluctuating framerate that literally has no cap, reaching up to 1000+ fps in the menus and 200-300 fps while racing, creating this weird stutter effect which makes the game look way worse than it should. Limiting the game's FPS via graphics driver settings (Nvidia control panel, AMD Catalyst, etc.) fixes this and makes the game look a lot smoother, but it seems unnecessary.Second on visuals, hitting a tire stack (which most of the tracks will have them on the curbs of corners) will cause the game to freeze for half a second, then resume. Why it does this, I have no idea, but it's incredibly jarring when it happens.Last but not least on the visual front, many tracks have clipping textures on the ground where you can see the grass rise through the road.It's a bunch of rough spots in a game that's otherwise very stylish in terms of its visual appearance.The AI...oh boy. As much as I love the Gran Turismo series, the AI in those games is way too slow in the corners and guess what? That happens here, in a completely unrelated game as well, in almost every race except for Pinzana, one of the later races, where they will relentlessly chase you by driving so hard they smash into the outer barrier......and THEN the AI will glitch out and eitherA) drive endlessly into those barriers or trees in front of them instead of turning 90 degreesorB) drive endlessly out of bounds if they get knocked out either by the player or the other AI drivers.Speaking of Pinzana, the menu says it's a 5-lap race which makes sense considering the simple layout and A-class competition. However, it's only 2 laps when you start it. Also, one of the other races, Bersenbrück, says it's a 3 lap race when it's really a 2 lap race in-game AND has a drastically different layout than the menu map suggests for the latter half of each lap.Finally, here's my subjective opinion on the camera: There should have been multiple camera options, like Little Racers STREET. Give the player a camera closer to the car's rear bumper so the player can actually see corners that are coming up without blindly guessing based on the mini-map. Typically, this isn't much of a problem in top-down racing games, but due to this game's realistic physics (and the fact that braking too late can cause a bad spin or crash) this problem is made much worse than it should be.All this adds up to a game with style over substance, a great concept let down by some odd design choices. Most of the above would more than likely still apply in multiplayer, if there's even anyone playing online.I haven't checked and I'm in no rush to be honest.Recommendation:If you like top-down racing games,Little Racers STREETorToybox Turbosare both fantastic. The latter is short but sweet, and the former is a little on the low budget side, but it'll take you time to do everything it has to offer. If you're looking for a good simulation racing game, well I'll admit I'm not a sim racer expert butAutomobilistais one I've been going back to again and again. There may not be much gameplay progression, but there is a lot of fun racing to be had, and now that mods are coming out, it will only get better with time.It's just a real shame about Cranks and Goggles. I know this was released out of early access in public beta form (which I'm really against this and hopefully this doesn't become a standard practice considering another gameBIOSdid almost the same thing; in my opinion,early access IS opt-in public beta) and hopefully updates make this better. That being said, in its current form it's missing that extra layer of polish and I can't recommend it unless you've played everything else racing-wise on Steam.Also: According to The Wayback Machine, the original early access version back in June was already mostly content-complete after being ""in development for 10 months"", so what happened in the other 6 months leading to the 1.0 beta release? Also, 3 months for a small bugfix? That's...odd."
76561198066055408,Not Recommended,451990,30872156,Posted: 1 April,all,steelcitydubber,"This game is hard. Really hard. At the moment i'm 2 hours in, which is a LOT of 3 minute races. My average finish is 5th or last and i've fluked a 2nd and a 3rd out of probably 100 races so far. I have upgraded my car which has made it worse! Upgrades are a good idea, but perhaps you could specify what to upgrade (just handling would be my choice at the moment, adding speed later)The AI is good, they mess up occassionaly and don't slow down for you!At the moment, controlling the car is just too hard. Trying to get a feel for the car is impossible. It oversteers like a RWD if you let off the throttle before a slight change in direction, but understeers madly if you don't. This felt exciting and interesting when I first started - I couldnt wait for the learning curve to kick in and for things to improve, however it is so difficult to understand what is going on, and the margin for error so tiny, that the excitement gave way to frustration and is now bordering on apathy. (note: i'm a seasoned gamer and I love racing games, driving sims etc). I would understand if the starter car was underpowered but had fairly decent handling, but it doesnt. You nail the throttle to keep up, but have to guess the corner before you can see it in order to start a drift, which seems the only way to corner competitively. If you keep the trottle on you understeer into the wall. Let off while turning and you spin instantly.I feel like I have started the game in 'insane' mode, with all assists off.Perhaps its would be easier with a controller or even a steering wheel.Watch the launch video - those amazing turns are very very rare and feel a lot like luck! Most of the time I end up clipping a fence which spins me around and its race over.  If you make more than 1 mistake on the first lap you may as well restart straight away, there is no way you are going to finish 3rd once the other cars are not visible on the minimap.Which is another issue. You cant see where you are going, and you can't adjust the zoom even a tiny bit. You need to watch your fishtailing car so hard to keep it from spinning that you cant dare look too far ahead, and given the way the screen spins it is very difficult to get used to the subtle changes in direction of the car which give away how it is reacting to your driving, and that's how you would learn to tame these beastly machines.For those who would say 'its actually a great sim of how these old cars used to drive' ... terrible grip, crazy weight distribution, unforgiveable handling... perhaps. but they weren't driving while looking down on them from above, with only a second of track visible and the car turning constantly on the screen. I'm also not sure if they ever drove this fast on gravel or sand, which is what the surface feels like. Maybe a level of tracks comprised of only tarmac would make the start easier. Perhaps also with walls that didnt automatically spin you around if you hit them, like the fences and boxes do.FYI the first and last tracks seem a lot more forgiving than the middle tracks, I must have now played the second track 40 times in a row and I'm not getting any better!, i should be learning and improving.It is fun. And cheap at the moment, but it should be called 'impossible race' IMO. Please consider an easier start, a tutorial in case i'm missing something, and a slightly less severe starting difficulty somehow.Its hard to know whether to recommend this or not, at the moment i'd go for 'interesting and addictive but sabotaged by impossible learning curve and vicious starting difficulty'. I'm going to leave the game here but I will be back for every update in the hope that they tweak the handling in the direction of 'rewarding' rather than 'frustrating'.Pro: Looks great. Right up my street without being too 'crossy road' blocky.Pro: The rest of the package - levels look great fun, i like the idea of progressing through classes only when you win enough. A lot of love has gone into this so far.Pro: Is hard enough to be interesting and challenging...Pro: the odd occasiion you get a corner spot on is very satisfying but feels too much like luck.Con: ...but too hard to be rewarding at the moment.Con: Very hard to see what is actually going on with the car. I still cant work out if im driving a FWD or RWD car, it seems to have characteristics of both without the benefits of either.! Where is the weight? The physics need tweaking one way or another.I think this game will go in the right direction, so i'm going to recommend it, but it was close, i wont be playing for a while because i dont want to hate this game!"
